{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "chinese-phil-expert",
    "senderColor": "cyan",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Report updated with intersubjectivity and philosophical experiments sections",
    "content": "Updated the Analysis Report at `/Users/el/Dropbox/10.Kernel/11.Vault/Tower/L. Legenravend/49 Workspace/Chinese Philosophy/Analysis Report.md`. Three changes made:\n\n1. **Section 2 (Reversal Argument), point 2**: Added a cross-reference note pointing to the new Section 10 on intersubjectivity, since the projection of 现象仁 onto others is where the intersubjectivity problem first surfaces.\n\n2. **Section 9 (Qualifications), point 4**: Updated the formalization gap qualification to note that \"philosophical experiments\" are not merely programmatic but are actively conducted within the essays themselves, with a cross-reference to new Section 11.\n\n3. **Added Section 10: Intersubjectivity (主体间性) and the Natural Transformation** -- covers how the eta-based structural commensurability account differs from all four traditional Chinese answers (Mencian 推己及人, Zhuangzi's 子非鱼, Buddhist 他心通, Neo-Confucian 理同), and identifies the closest precedent as a functionalist reading of Xunzi's 礼 theory.\n\n4. **Added Section 11: The Essays as Philosophical Experiments (哲学实验)** -- identifies precedent in classical Chinese philosophy (Mencius's 孺子入井, Zhuangzi's parables), analyzes five specific essays/passages as experiments on the reader, and flags the critical translation implication that experiential sequence is load-bearing and must not be reorganized.\n"
  }
}
